<subSubSection id="70B417B5FFC4FFC91687FDBDFC855A00" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3811443EFFC4FFC91687FDBDFC855A00" blockId="28.[151,1437,468,891]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC91687FDBDFE805B4D" bold="true" box="[199,338,540,566]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="FFAE3FBDFFC4FFC91718FDBCFE225B4D" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[344,496,540,566]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Bitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caudalis">
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC91718FDBCFE225B4D" box="[344,496,540,566]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Bitis caudalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is commonly found in arid western regions of southern Africa, with southern 
<collectingCountry id="40B904AEFFC4FFC9130AFDBDFA4E5B4D" box="[1354,1436,540,566]" name="Angola" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Angola</collectingCountry>
as its northern distribution limit (
<bibRefCitation id="5C3F39CFFFC4FFC91452FDE1FD7B5B21" author="Branch, W. R." box="[530,681,576,602]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="159" refId="ref34681" refString="Branch, W. R. (2018) Snakes of Angola: An annotated checklist. Amphibian &amp; Reptile Conservation, General Section, 12 (2), e 159, 41 - 82." type="journal article" year="2018">Branch 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5C3F39CFFFC4FFC914F7FDE0FC705B21" author="Marques, M. P. &amp; Ceriaco, L. M. P. &amp; Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M." box="[695,930,576,603]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 501" refId="ref38562" refString="Marques, M. P., Ceriaco, L. M. P., Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M. (2018) Diversity and distribution of the amphibians and terrestrial reptiles of Angola atlas of historical and bibliographic records (1840 - 2017). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Series 4, 65 (Supplement 2), 1 - 501." type="journal article" year="2018">
Marques 
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC91562FDE0FC8E5B21" box="[802,860,576,602]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). It is an arenicolous species that belongs to the dwarf adders subgenus, 
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC91794FDC5FD875B05" box="[468,597,612,638]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Calechidna</emphasis>
, endemic to southern Africa (
<bibRefCitation id="5C3F39CFFFC4FFC915E9FDC5FB565B05" author="Barlow, A. &amp; Wuster, W. &amp; Kelly, C. M. R. &amp; Branch, W. R. &amp; Phelps, T. &amp; Tolley, K. A." box="[937,1156,612,638]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1234 - 1248" refId="ref33576" refString="Barlow, A., Wuster, W., Kelly, C. M. R., Branch, W. R., Phelps, T. &amp; Tolley, K. A. (2019) Ancient habitat shifts and organismal diversification are decoupled in the African viper genus Bitis (Serpentes: Viperidae). Journal of Biogeography, 46 (6), 1234 - 1248. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jbi. 13578" type="journal article" year="2019">
Barlow 
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC91245FDC4FBED5B05" box="[1029,1087,612,638]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
). The extant specimen is within the expected range for 
<taxonomicName id="FFAE3FBDFFC4FFC917AEFD28FDBC5BD9" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[494,622,648,674]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Bitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caudalis">
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC917AEFD28FDBC5BD9" box="[494,622,648,674]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">B. caudalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but as Ferreira did not properly study the specimens from the last part of Newton’s Expedition, it was not cited or identified. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation id="5C3F39CFFFC4FFC9152DFD0DFB835BBD" author="Barlow, A. &amp; Wuster, W. &amp; Kelly, C. M. R. &amp; Branch, W. R. &amp; Phelps, T. &amp; Tolley, K. A." box="[877,1105,684,710]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1234 - 1248" refId="ref33576" refString="Barlow, A., Wuster, W., Kelly, C. M. R., Branch, W. R., Phelps, T. &amp; Tolley, K. A. (2019) Ancient habitat shifts and organismal diversification are decoupled in the African viper genus Bitis (Serpentes: Viperidae). Journal of Biogeography, 46 (6), 1234 - 1248. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jbi. 13578" type="journal article" year="2019">
Barlow 
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC91586FD0CFC2D5BBD" box="[966,1023,684,710]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
recovered two mitochondrial lineages of 
<taxonomicName id="FFAE3FBDFFC4FFC9175AFD70FE4A5B91" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[282,408,720,746]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Bitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caudalis">
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC9175AFD70FE4A5B91" box="[282,408,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">B. caudalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which they treated as two different taxa. The limited sampling by the authors did not yield firm conclusions, but showcased the need for further studies, given the apparent cryptic nature of 
<taxonomicName id="FFAE3FBDFFC4FFC912B6FD54FAA75A75" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[1270,1397,756,782]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Bitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caudalis">
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC912B6FD54FAA75A75" box="[1270,1397,756,782]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">B. caudalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, no Angolan material was evaluated.A detailed taxonomic revision of the case is being prepared by Ceríaco 
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC916D7FC9CFF035A2D" box="[151,209,828,854]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al.</emphasis>
(in prep). This specimen appears to be relatively hornless, a characteristic that seems to be common in this species (
<bibRefCitation id="5C3F39CFFFC4FFC916B7FCC1FDD35A01" author="Spawls, S. &amp; Branch, W. R." box="[247,513,864,890]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref40292" refString="Spawls, S. &amp; Branch, W. R. (2020) The Dangerous Snakes of Africa. Bloomsbury Wildlife, London, 336 pp." type="book" year="2020">Spawls &amp; Branch 2020</bibRefCitation>
; Ceríaco &amp; Marques 
<emphasis id="0ADA982CFFC4FFC914AFFCC0FC945A01" box="[751,838,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">in press</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
